      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walk Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with 3 minutes of brisk walking to gently wake up the foot and ankle. Pay attention to any tightness in the plantar fascia before transitioning to running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at the easiest end of your easy pace — around 6:12/km or softer. If you notice any foot discomfort at any point, drop back to a walk immediately. Run-walk format: 3 minutes running, 1 minute walking, repeated. This is not about pace — it's about load management.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish with 3 minutes of easy walking. Take a moment to notice how the foot feels — no pain is the goal, not speed or distance.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 minutes of brisk walking before any running. Gentle ankle circles and calf raises (if pain-free) are a good addition.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes to close out the session. Gentle calf stretching afterward — tight calves increase plantar fascia load.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Welcome back, James. This first run of the week is purely about re-establishing the habit and checking in with how your foot is tolerating load. Your physio has cleared you for 20 minutes of easy running only, and that's exactly what this is. We're working from your Daniels-Gilbert zones, and right now the only zone that matters is easy — around 6:12/km or gentler. The run-walk format here isn't a step backward; it's a smart way to manage cumulative load on the plantar fascia while still getting the aerobic signal. Your pre-injury pace-zone index of 46.5 tells us your fitness base is solid — the goal right now is just to protect the structure so you can rebuild on it. If there's zero foot pain during or after this run, that's a win. If there's any discomfort, walk the remainder and note it for your physio.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Load Check\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 minutes of walking to warm up the foot gradually. Notice morning stiffness — if the foot is stiff from Tuesday, that's useful information to share with your physio.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Continue the run-walk format: 3 minutes easy running at ~6:12/km, 1 minute walking. If Tuesday felt great and pain-free, you can try 4 minutes running to 1 minute walking. If Tuesday was at all tender, stay with 3:1. Let the foot guide the ratio.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 minutes of easy walking. Check in with how the foot feels compared to after Tuesday's run — is it better, the same, or worse? That trend is your feedback.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes before starting any running. If the foot feels stiff or sore from Tuesday's run, this session can be replaced with a 20-minute easy walk — that still counts as productive recovery work.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Easy 3-minute walk to finish. Gentle calf and Achilles stretching if pain-free. Avoid aggressive plantar fascia stretching immediately post-run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek session is your load check. The key question is: how did Tuesday go? If Tuesday felt fine during the run and you had no lingering soreness afterward, you can be a little more confident today. If there was any foot discomfort, scale back to a walk-dominant session — and that's genuinely fine, not a failure. We're building a trend here, not proving anything on any single day. The 48-hour gap from Tuesday is intentional — it gives the plantar fascia time to adapt without accumulating fatigue. Your current weekly volume of around 6-8 km is manageable; we're being conservative because the foundation matters far more than the pace right now.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Weekend Easy Long Run — Time on Feet\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes to start. Saturday morning is often when the plantar fascia is stiffest — take the warmup walk seriously today.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This is your 'long run' but it's capped at 20 minutes just like the other sessions — physio clearance comes first. Run at the easiest effort you can manage, 6:00-6:12/km. Walk breaks whenever needed. Think of this as aerobic maintenance, not a workout to push through.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3-5 minutes at the end. This is the most important cooldown of the week — Saturday's run sets the tone for how the foot feels into the following week.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk at least 3-5 minutes before running on Saturday. Morning foot stiffness is very common with plantar fasciitis — don't skip this step. If the foot feels notably worse than midweek, consider making Saturday a full walking session instead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3-5 minutes to finish. Elevate the foot for a few minutes afterward if it feels at all worked. Check in on how it feels 24 hours later — Sunday morning is a useful data point for your physio.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your preference is for a Saturday long run, and we're honoring that — though right now 'long run' means the same 20-minute cap as the rest of the week. That's not a permanent ceiling; it's where we are right now based on your physio's guidance. The value of this session is consistency and routine: building the habit of the Saturday run so that when your physio clears you for more volume, the pattern is already there. Your Daniels-Gilbert easy pace range is 5:25-6:12/km, and for this phase we're working at the slower end — 6:00-6:12/km — because the foot, not the fitness, is the limiting factor right now. Think of this week's three sessions as a test run (literally) — the data you gather about how the foot responds is exactly what your physio needs to progress your clearance. How the foot feels on Sunday morning after Saturday's run is one of the most useful signals you can report back.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
